Inside were 3 bottles of boat cleaning solution that were each inside seperate zip lock plastic bags. One of the bottles was found with a loose cap, and had leaked it's contents throughout the box. DurationRel: 3 and MitigateEffect: The bottles and packaging were all brought over to QA in an identifiable damaged hazmat tote. At 0558 EST, ERTS was contacted by XPO Logistics (LSL) about a cargo release. It was reported that due to a forklift puncture approximately 20 gallons of Nalco Trac114 Plus (Hazardous - UN1824) was released. XPO stated that the released product was contained to the dock floor at door #95. The terminal requested a contractor out to clean and contain the spill, and to transfer the un-impacted product into a new tote. ERTS dispatched E3 Environmental to conduct cleanup operations.  At 0800 EST, contractors arrived onsite and confirmed 20 gallons of product released to a 10' x 15' area of the dock floor. The remaining material in the damaged tote was pumped out into a new tote. Absorbents were worked into the impacted area and collected. The damaged tote was then cut up and containerized with the spent absorbents into (4) 55 gallon poly drums. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column168: At 0723 ET, XPO notified ERTS of a cargo release at terminal NDE. It was reported that approximately 2 gallons of Sodium Hydroxide were released from a 55 gallon poly drum due to improper loading. The release impacted the inside of trailer #3176732 and the dock floor. ERTS dispatched Hepaco to conduct cleanup operations. At 1430 EST, Hepaco arrived onsite and confirmed 2 gallons of product released to a 5' x 5' area of the concrete dock floor due to a forklift puncture. Absorbents were worked into the spill and then collected into a 55 gallon poly drum. The damaged drum was placed into a 95 gallon poly overpack. All waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

At 1258 EST, XPO Logistics UPW notified ERTS of a 10 gallon release of UN3352 Lambda-Cyhalothrin from multiple 1 gallon plastic jugs due to a forklift puncture, impacting the trailer floor. ERTS dispatched Clean Harbors to conduct cleanup operations. At 1530 EST, Clean Harbors personnel arrived onsite and confirmed 6 gallons of product released from (6) 1 gallon poly jugs. The release impacted a 10' x 5' area of the trailer floor. The damaged boxes and jugs were removed and placed into a 55 gallon poly drum along with the spent absorbents from cleanup. All waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column168: At 0630 ET, XPO Logistics notified ERTS of a cargo release at terminal UPO. The release impacted the inside of trailer #4633083 and the dock floor. ERTS dispatched EnviroServe to conduct cleanup operations. At 1040 EST, crew arrived onsite and confirmed 5 gallons of product released to a 7' x 5' area of the dock floor and a 3' x 1' area of the trailer floor. The remaining material was transferred out of the damaged tote and into a new one to be shipped on. Absorbents were then worked into the impacted areas and then collected. The damaged tote was cut up and containerized along with spent absorbents into (2) 55 gallon poly drums. All waste was left onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

XPO Logistics NNA called to report a hazardous cargo release inside a trailer. At 0630 EST Hepaco arrived onsite and confirmed 20 gallons of product released to an 8' x 20' area of the trailer floor and a 5' x 15' area of the dock floor. The damaged drum was placed into a 95 gallon metal drum and all spent absorbents were collected into (4) 55 gallon metal drums. All waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

SequenceEvent: damaged hazmat brought to the damage area. placed in lined tote and moved to drain mats in incoming damaged hazmat/LQ area. in-house cleanup, awaiting disposition. DescribePack: bottles found at bottom of package. most appear to have anywhere from traces of leaked material to the entire cap being pushed out due to hardened material. some bottles coated in the dried material. all the hazardous material inside and outside their respective bottles has solidified. according to detailed information on the product it may have polymerized due to changes in temperature: "Containers must be heavily insulated or shipped under refrigeration. An inhibitor such as hydroquinone, hydroquinone methyl ester and dimethyl t-butylphenol is added to keep the chemical from initiating polymerization. The chemical may polymerize exothermically if heated or contaminated with strong acid or base. If the polymerization takes place inside a container, the container may rupture violently." the bottles all are distorted in shape due to the solidified material. DurationRel: 2 and MitigateEffect: none of the release escaped the outer packaging beyond some light staining. package was placed in lined tote and moved to drain mats.

column168: 1024 ET, XPO Logistics (XCF) contacted ERTS to report a cargo release. They confirmed the cap was loose, causing the release. Absorbents were worked into the impacted areas and collected into a 55 gallon poly drum. The tote cap was secured, and a slosh test was conducted to determine the tote was good to ship onto the consignee. The waste was left onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

Crew confirmed the lid popped open due to load shift in transit. column25: University of Texas Health and Science Center
column168: The forklift operator was unloading a pallet of poly drums off of a truck at the 10 day intransit facility. While removing the pallet, there were two plastic containers wedged in between two pallets that were used to fill the void space. At first glance it was hard to tell that they were both cross-palletized. When the forklift operator pulled the pallet of drums out of the slot the plastic containers that were loaded in between the pallets fell forward resulting in one of the lids popping off upon impact.
column169: Recommended actions to take in the future to avoid a recurrence is: 1) to inspect the way containers are stacked before removing the pallets, 2) alternatively, use of vermiculate bags to fill in gaps rather than using waste containers, and 3) unstack double-stacked containers before removing pallets from the truck and then double stack the containers once in the warehouse.

column168: I WAS ASSIGNED TO WORK ON THE LEAKING PACKAGE AT 14:30; THE PACKAGE HAD ALREADY BEEN RETURNED TO THE PSC FOR PROCESSING BY ANOTHER RESPONDER. THE PACKAGE WAS ORIGINALLY FOUND ON SD6 IN OR NEAR DOOR 122 AT 13:40. UPON OPENING THE PACKAGE I DISCOVERED THAT THE INNER BOXES FOR THE MERCHANDISE (CRC GLASS CLEANER, AEROSOL CANS) WERE LABELED AS LIMITED QUANTITIES; THE OUTER BOX DID NOT HAVE ANY LABELING THAT INDICATED THIS. AFTER CHECKING THE SDS FOR THE PRODUCT IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT THE PRODUCT WAS LISTED AS "AEROSOLS, NON-FLAMMABLE, LIMITED QUANTITY, UN 1950, 2.2." I INFORMED THE DAY SORT RMP, THAT THE LEAKING PACKAGE WAS POTENTIALLY AN UNDECLARED HAZMAT. CALLED THE HMSC TO REPORT THE INCIDENT. FOLLOWING THIS, I WAS INSTRUCTED TO PUT THE PACKAGE ON HOLD FOR ADG COMPLIANCE AND CONTAINERIZE THE LEAKING PACKAGE WITHIN A DMP BAG AWAITING RELEASE FOR PROCESSING.

A Veolia employee was trans loading the 55 gal poly open top (551H2) drum at Veolia's 10 day in-transit facility in Baytown, TX, utilizing a forklift with parrot beaks when the drum fell from the beaks.  The drum landed upright, but some liquid splashed out of the top of the drum.  The spilled liquid was cleaned up.  Further inspection of the drum revealed no recognizable damage or failure of the drum or associated drum lid and ring.  However, it was identified that the drum was UN rated for solids, or inner packages containing liquids. The material in the drum was all free liquid.  All 5 drums of the material were over packed into salvage drums to minimize any further potential leakage during transportation to the receiving facility.
column169: Veolia employees will be retrained to perform a complete inspection of containers and ensure containers of waste are capable and/or properly rated for the material before accepting and shipping containers from the shipper.

column168: MC Tank Transport notified ERTS of a tank release at Limestone Rest Stop in Pontiac, IL. It was reported that Farmin DM4250M (UN2735) was released from a tank trailer due to a very slow drip in the valve. The release impacted the asphalt only. ERTS dispatched an environmental contractor (Hepaco). Hepaco is on-site and has stopped the valve from releasing.  Hepaco has tightened the bolts on the valve and confirmed the release is no longer active. Hepaco stated after further assessment, an estimated 10 gallons of product released measuring 10' x 3' on asphalt. Hepaco used granular absorbents to clean the impacted area of asphalt and pads to clean the impacted to the tanker body. All waste were collected, containerized and taken off site for pending disposal.

column168: On October 13, 2021, at 0130 ET, XPO Logistics Terminal LJS experienced a release of UN1814 Potassium Hydroxide “Stealth”. Due to a forklift puncture (2) 2.5 gallon poly jugs of product released impacting the trailer floor and concrete lot below. ERTS dispatched E3 Environmental to the site to perform all cleanup and remediation activities. At 0455 ET, E3 Environmental personnel arrived on site and confirmed approximately 2.5 gallons of product released to a 4’ x 4’ area of the trailer floor and a 1’ x 1’ area of the concrete lot below. Biosorb was worked into the impacted areas and collected. All cleanup debris and the damaged freight were then containerized into (4) 55 gallon poly drums. All waste was staged on site for terminal personnel to manage.

column168: FULLY LABELED HAZ-MAT SHIPMENT WAS VISUALLY DISCOVERED WET IN APPEARANCE BY THE HAZ-MAT AUDITOR ON TWILIGHT SORT. WITHOUT TOUCHING THE PKG SHE EVACUATED THE AREA AND NOTIFIED HER IMMEDIATE SUPERVISOR. DMP WAS CONTACTED AND WITHIN A FEW MINUTES A RESPONDER ARRIVED, DONNING THE PROPER PPE. AFTER FOLLOWING THE DECISION TREE   APPROPRIATE RESPONSE SHEET, THE DAMAGE WAS CONTAINED (NO SPILLAGE OUTSIDE OF CARTON), THEN TRANSPORTED TO THE DMP PROCESSING AREA. CLOSER INSPECTION REVEALED THAT THE CAP ON 1 OF 4 PLASTIC 5 LITER JUGS WAS LOOSE BY A FULL ROTATION, CAUSING APPROX. 12 OZ OF THE LIQUID FROM A CONTAINER OF THE NON-HAZARDOUS SECTION OF A 2-PART KIT TO SPILL THROUGH THE BREACH AND INTO THE BOTTOM OF THE CARTON. THE INNER PACKING MATERIAL CONSISTED OF A DOUBLE CORRUGATED BOX CONFIGURATION AND THE OUTER CARTON WAS A SINGLEWALL FIBERBOARD BOX, RATED AT A 44 LBS PER INCH EDGE CRUSH TEST (ECT).
CLERK TOLD ME HE HAD A HAZMAT LEAKING. DONNED PPE AND RESPONDED

BOTTOM OF BOX WAS WET, PACKAGE CAME APART ON ROLLERS AND CONTENTS FELL ON FLOOR. SUPERVISOR GOT ALL EMPLOYEES OUT OF BUILDING, GOT PPE AND WENT THROUGH DECISION TREE WHICH LED HIM TO CALL DISTRICT SPILL COORDINATOR

EMPLOYEE DROPPED THE PACKAGE ON THE IRREG CART. THERE WAS A 1 GALLON BOTTLE OF ALCOHOL WHICH CRACKED BECAUSE OF THE HANDLING OF THE PACKAGE. ONLY ABOUT 2 OUNCES LEAKED FROM THE GALLON. THE REST OF THE GALLON WAS ABSORBED AND PROCESSED THROUGH THE DMP.
LOOSE CAP WAS FOUND ON PACKAGE ALL CONTENTS DISCARDED

column168: At 1702 ET, XPO notified ERTS of a cargo release at terminal LEP. Absorbents were worked into the impacted areas and the containerized along with the damaged pail into a 30 gallon poly overpack. The waste was left onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column168: On October 13, 2021 at 0417 EST, XPO Logistics NBM reported an unknown amount of UN1760 Voracor CK 481 was released in trailer 321-6175 and on the concrete beneath the trailer from a 275 gallon tote that was punctured by a forklift. Terminal personnel placed absorbents to contain the release. ERTS dispatched Miller Environmental to conduct cleanup operations. At 0735 EST, Miller personnel arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 200 gallons of product released to a 28' x 8' area of the trailer, 30' x 20' area of the concrete dock and a 28' x 8' area of the asphalt lot below the trailer. Crew confirmed approximately 60 gallons of product was still in the damaged tote, this was transferred out into a 55 gallon poly drum. A drum vac was also utilized to collect the free standing liquid located in all the impacted areas. All liquids were placed into (3) 55 gallon poly closed top drums. Once the free liquid was removed, absorbents were worked into the impacted areas. The spent absorbents were then collected and containerized along with the cut up damaged tote into (12) 55 gallon poly drums. All waste was then staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column168: On October 7, 2021 at 2058 EST, XPO Logistics (NMP) called to report a hazardous cargo release. It was reported a 5 gallon plastic pail of a UN1760 Sodium Hydroxide leaked 1 cup of material onto the trailer floor. XPO stated they had completed clean up and placed all waste into an 8 gallon metal drum. ERTS dispatched a Hepaco to containerize the waste properly and ensure clean up is completed. At 0045 EST, Hepaco personnel arrived onsite and located the 5 gallon plastic pail of a UN1760 "Warren Super 500" placed inside of a poly lined 8 gallon metal drum. Hepaco spoke with the site contact who advised he was told by the previous shift lead the spill was mostly dried to the dock surface and no clean up was needed. Hepaco confirmed there was no standing liquid or spill in the vicinity. Crew placed the liner and its contents into a 30 gallon poly drum. The 8 gallon metal drum was inspected and confirmed not impacted. All waste was left onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column168: On October 13, 2021, at 1541 ET XPO Logistics ULA notified ERTS of a 2 gallon release of UN3082 Epoplex LS60 LF Yellow A from a 55 gallon metal drum due to a forklift puncture, impacting the tail of the trailer floor. column168: On October 7, 2021 XPO Logistics Terminal XDM reported 5 pounds if UN1759 "One Shot Detergent" was released on the dock from (2) 55 pound paper bags that were punctured by a broken pallet. ERTS dispatched Clean Harbors to conduct cleanup operations. At 0925 EST, Clean Harbors personnel arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 100 pounds of product released to a 20' x 15' area of the trailer, dock floor, and concrete lot below the trailer. The broken pallet caused the bags to fall and tear open. Crew confirmed 18 bags were found damaged and were containerized along with all released product into (3) 55 & (1) 65 gallon poly drums. All waste was left onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

All waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

At 2100 ET, XPO Logistics notified ERTS of a cargo release at XQC. It was reported that 55 gallons of UN184 released from a 55 gallon poly drum due to a forklift accident impacting the trailer floor. ERTS dispatched Hepaco to conduct all onsite cleanup operations. At 2305 EST, Hepaco personnel arrived onsite and confirmed 55 gallons of product released to a 4' x 4' area of the trailer floor and a 50' x 10' area of the concrete lot below. Absorbents were deployed to contain the release and then worked in to collect all material. The damaged drum was containerized into an 85 gallon poly overpack. All impacted absorbents were then collected into (3) 55 gallon poly drums. All waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

At 0454 ET, XPO Logistics notified ERTS of a cargo release at XNB. It was reported that 1 gallon of UN1760 “Chlorinated Degreaser” was released from a 1 gallon plastic jug due to a forklift accident. The release occurred on the dock. ERTS dispatched New England Disposal Technologies (NEDT) to conduct cleanup operations. At 0935 EST, NEDT personnel arrived onsite and confirmed 1 gallon of product released to a 1' x 1' area of the dock floor. Terminal placed absorbents down prior to their arrival. These were worked into the impacted area and then collected along with the damaged jug into a 55 gallon poly drum. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

On October 22, 2021, at 1022 EST, ERTS was contacted by XPO Logistics (XSD) about a cargo release. It was reported that due to unknown reasons, approximately 2 cups of Octocrylene (Hazardous - UN3082) released to the trailer floor from a 55 gallon poly drum. XPO requested a contractor out to clean and contain the spill. ERTS dispatched Atlantic Response to conduct all onsite cleanup operations. On October 22, 2021, at 1300 EST, Atlantic Response personnel arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 1 pint of product released to a 4' x 4' area of the trailer floor. Crew also advised terminal personnel had placed the leaking 55 gallon poly drum into a 30  gallon poly overpack because it was the only container they had available. The damaged drum was removed from the 30 gallon and containerized into an 85 gallon poly overpack. Absorbents were then worked into the impacted area and then collected into a 55 gallon poly drum. All waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

On October 25, 2021 at 0751 ET, XPO Logistics (UDV terminal) contacted ERTS regarding a UN1090, Acetone, 3, PG II release that occurred at 0745 ET. It was advised that up to 35 gallons of product released from a 55 gallon metal drum to the trailer floor and lot below due to a forklift puncture. ERTS dispatched Environmental Works to conduct all onsite cleanup operations. On October 25, 2021, at 0927 EST, Environmental Works personnel arrived onsite and confirmed 6 gallons of product released to a 2' x 3' area of the trailer floor and a 1' x 10' area of the asphalt lot below. Crew containerized the damaged drum into a 95 gallon metal overpack. Absorbents were then worked into the impacted areas and collected into a 55 gallon metal drum. All waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column168: On October 25, 2021 at 1029 ET, XPO notified ERTS of a cargo release at customer location 1710 N Expy, Griffin, GA. It was reported that approximately 20 gallons of printer ink released from a 330 gallon metal tote impacting the inside of the trailer. ERTS dispatched Hepaco to conduct all onsite cleanup operations. At 1235 EST, Hepaco personnel arrived onsite and confirmed 20 gallons of product released to a 1' x 25' area of the trailer floor and a 10' x 20' area of the asphalt lot below the trailer. Crew advised the valve on the tote was cracked open and there was no cam-lock fitting on the tote. A new fitting was obtained and the tote was re-secured for shipment. Absorbents were worked into the impacted areas and then collected. All waste was containerized into (2) 55 gallon metal and (1) 55 gallon poly drums. The waste drums were transported to the XPO terminal located in Atlanta, GA for terminal personnel to manage.

At 0851 ET, XPO Logistics terminal LBY contacted ERTS regarding the release of UN3264 Cesco Protect 7010. It was reported that a 55 gallon poly drum was punctured by a forklift during loading operations and released approximately 1 quart of material onto the concrete dock floor. ERTS is coordinated a response with HMR Hazmat of Conroe, TX to conduct the cleanup. At 1100 EST, HMR personnel arrived onsite and confirmed 0.5 gallons of product released to a 2' x 2' area of the concrete dock floor. The damaged drum was placed into a 95 gallon poly drum. Absorbents were worked into the impacted area and then collected into the waste drum. The waste was left onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

RESPONDER ARRIVED AT WORK AT 3:30AM TO THE HAZMAT ALREADY ON THE COUNTER IN THE HAZMAT CAGE WITH NO LINER OR SPILL TRAY UNDER IT. THE BOTTOM OF THE HAZMAT WAS CLEARLY WET AS THE CONTENTS OF THE PACKAGE HAD SOAKED THROUGH.

column42: SULFURIC ACID WITH MORE THAN 51 PERCENT ACID
column168: At 0535 XPO reported a spill of UN1850 Sulfuric Acid "Rooto Professional Drain Opener" to the trailer floor. The cause was due to improper loading. ERTS contacted EnviroServe to conduct cleanup operations. At 1030 EST, EnviroServe personnel arrived onsite and confirmed 1 gallon of product released from (2) 1.5 gallon jugs. The release impacted a 9' x 3' area of the trailer floor and a 2' x 4' area of the asphalt lot. Absorbents were worked into the impacted areas and then collected. All waste including the damaged jugs and spent absorbents were containerized into (2) 55 gallon poly drums. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column168: SequenceEvent: PACKAGE LEFT IN HAZMAT CAGE ON 10-26-21 DescribePack: DUE TO INSUFFICIENT INNER PACKING, INNER BOX MOVEMENT CAUSED LOOSENING OF CAPS WHICH LEAKED ABOUT 16 OUNCES FROM 1 OF THE 2 BOTTLES. OUTER BOX SOILED, WET, SOFTENED. BOTH ITEMS SHOW NO VISIBLE DAMAGE ONLY LESS LIQUID IN 1 OF 2 ITEMS BY 16 OZ. APPROXIMATELY. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: BOTH ITEMS & CLEAN UP SUPPLIES WAS PUT IN A PLASTIC HAZMAT BAG WITH HAZORB AND TWIST TIE AND THEN SEALED IN A SALVAGE DRUM.

SequenceEvent: During the OVN Sort the wet package was brought over to the hazmat cage with signs of internal leakage. The package was placed into a bag to be processed. After processing it was then placed inside a clear hazmat bag and then stored inside a salvage drum to be sent back to the shipper unless otherwise. DescribePack: The package failure was due most likely due to improper handling in the loading process and 1 of the 2 gallons containing  "CONVOTHERM CONVOCLEAN FORTE" having a loose cap causing the plastic seal to break and then leaking internally allowing the box to get wet and break open loosing the 2nd gallon. DurationRel: 2 and MitigateEffect: The cap was placed back on tightly, and then placed upright and tightly packaged inside a hazmat bag and a salvage drum to be sent back to the shipper unless otherwise.

SequenceEvent: package was unloaded and had a wet spot and set a side for inspection upon inspection product was found to be leaking from the cap box was then put in a hazardous waste container  and incident report was started. column168: I WAS TOLD THERE WAS A CORROSIVE LEAKER IN THE CAGE FOR ME TO PROCESS. UPON INSPECTION OF THE HAZARDOUS LEAKING PACKAGE, THE DECISION TREE LED ME TO FOLLOW THE RESPONSE SHEET FOR A LIQUID CORROSIVE. THE LIQUID WAS ONLY TWO GALLONS AND TYPICALLY REQUIRES SOLIDIFYING OF ANY PRODUCT THREE GALLONS OR LESS, HOWEVER, THIS WAS A TOXIC INHALATION HAZARD PICTOGRAM AS WELL AS SERIOUS EYE DAMAGE AND CORROSIVE TO TOUCH. THEREFORE, I DID NOT RISK OPENING AND SOLIDIFYING THE LIQUID DUE TO THE HAZARDS.
LEAKING PACKAGE WAS DISCOVERED ON THE BELT. RESPONDER RETRIEVED THE PACKAGE AND TOOK IT TO THE CLERK AREA TO PROCESS AND DISPOSE OF THE DAMAGE.
HAZARDOUS MATERIAL PACKAGE WAS REWRAP AT TRANSIT, TOP WAS CRACKED. LEAKED.

SPILL WAS CLEANED UP BY ANOTHER RESPONDER AND BROUGHT TO THE DMP. UPON INSPECTION THE STATE OF THE BOX WAS SATURATED AND ABOUT 1 OR 2 QUARTS OF THE PRODUCT HAD SPILLED OUT. THERE WAS NO ADDITIONAL CLEAN UP SUPPLIES OTHER THAN TOTE CONTAINING THE LEAKING BOX. THEREFORE I AM UNSURE IF THIS SPILL WAS CLEANED UP APPROPRIATELY. THE ENTIRE SHIPPING LABEL AND LASER COMPATIBLE PAPERS WERE TOO DAMAGED TO READ. THE WEIGHT OF THE BOX IS ESTIMATED AT 45 POUNDS. THE SATURATION OF THE BOX SUGGESTS THAT THE BOX WAS LOADED UPSIDE DOWN AND LEAKED. THE BOX ALSO APPEARS TO HAVE BEEN RE-TAPED AND THE CONTENTS WERE BAGGED IN A GARBAGE BAG. THIS SUGGESTS THAT MAYBE THE PACKAGE WAS RE-BOXED AT SOME POINT DURING ITS TRANSIT JOURNEY.

column168: XPO Logistics reported two drivers were switching trailers when they noticed product was leaking out of the rear of the trailer. ERTS dispatched Environmental Works to conduct cleanup operations. At 0815 EST, contractors arrived onsite and confirmed 2.5 gallons of product released to a 10 sq ft area of the trailer floor. Two 5 gallon pails of product were found damaged. Absorbents were worked into the impacted area and collected. Crew advised only the tail end of the trailer and landing gear/mud flaps/frame of trailer was impacted. No product reached the ground. Once the trailer was cleaned out the impacted pails and absorbents were then containerized into a 55 gallon metal drum. The waste was transported to the XPO terminal located in Henderson, CO for terminal personnel to manage.

column168: On October 28, 2021, at 0645 ET, XPO Logistics Terminal UBY experienced release of UN1824 “Cee-Bee J-84AL” from a 55 gallon poly drum due to a puncture by a broken pallet. ERTS dispatched Patriot Environmental to conduct all onsite cleanup operations. At 1320 EST, Patriot personnel arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 20 gallons of product released to the trailer floor and a 40’ x 10’ area of the asphalt parking lot. The remaining 35 gallons of product in the damaged drum was pumped out into a new 55 gallon poly drum. Absorbents were then worked into the impacted areas and collected. column168: At approximately 21:51, 10/13/21, a fire was reported entrain in UPSU600630 at Kingman, AZ. The local Kingman fire department extinguished the load and remove some of the charred cargo was damaged & removed by the fire department using water and class A foam.  Once extinguished, the shipments and train continued to destination, UPS North Bay, CA. Undeclared Hazmat containers were found in the items removed from the container by the Kingman FD.  These containers included a partially burned 5-gallon container of Flammable (UN1197), intact 5-gallon container of Flammable (UN1197) and a small package of Nitric Acid (UN2031).  It is unknown as to what caused the fire to start.  These materials will be returned to shipper or properly disposed of, disposition of hazmat containers has not yet occurred.

SOTX 1497 was found with wet staining from the top of the car in the Denver yard. Upon investigation, it was noted that multiple swing bolts were less than tool-tight, resulting in the leakage from out of the manway. The gasket was inspected and the swing bolts were tool-tightened. The outside of the car was cleaned by a contractor.

column162: HAZARDOUS MATERIALS AND EMERGENCY RESPONSE OFFICER
column168: A small visible release of product vapor was discovered during roll-by inspection of TILX 112594.  The car was isolated and assessed by local Fire Department and CP Contractors, with no further vapor release found.  The pressure relief device was found to have the spring retainer and spring not tight, allowing the poppet to be displaced and vapor to be released.  When the Girard T-Wrench was engaged into the spring retainer, the retainer was approximately ¼ turn from being tight. The spring retainer was adjusted, allowing the valve to re-seat properly.  Upon testing the pressure relief valve by adding pressure to the car, it was discovered that the pressure plate (B-right side) was found to leak at approximately 20 psi of applied pressure.  The bolts were torqued to specifications, with the bolts in that area found about ¼ turn loose.  When pressure was re-applied, however, the plate still leaked at approximately 20psi.   The car was then bled of pressure and secured.  Pending an OTMA-1 authorization, the car will be moved to homeshop for repair and re-certification.
column169: Upon discussion with CP's Contractor and the Shipper, it has been discovered that several similar incidents have occurred with the Girard safety valve, with the poppet not seating properly, due to retainer slack, allowing for vapor to be released.    I would suggest a closer look at any incidences that involve this model of safety valve to determine if there is any indications of slack developing over a period of time with the spring retainer system.

column168: While delivering product to a customer, our driver noticed liquid inside of his trailer.  He also identified an odor after backing into the customer's dock door.   Driver placed down dikes and absorbent pads to contain the spill.  Driver was requested by customer to move trailer away from building.  Once driver moved trailer away from building, customer called 911 at which point the Fire Department, Police, EMT, HazMat Response arrived onsite.  Neighboring facility was evacuated by Fire Department as precautionary measure who also closed off a local street as well.   HazMat Contractor arrived to scene at 1:30pm.  Hazmat contractor finished up around 4:45 pm EST, at which point the Univar Solutions driver was able to return to his dispatch site.    No injuries occurred / reported.   The liquid in trailer and on customer site was identified as N-Methylethoanolamine, which came from a tote scheduled to deliver to another customer.   The valve on the N-Methylethoanolamine was not in the closed position resulting in a release.

column42: SULFURIC ACID WITH MORE THAN 51 PERCENT ACID
column168: Univar arrived at customer's site with 1012 gallons of sulfuric acid on the trailer.  Our safe delivery form was completed with the customer and indicated customer could take 1300 gallons. Whilst at the end of the transfer the receiver approached our driver and advised the tank overfilled into their containment. Driver immediately stopped the transfer. Initial findings indicate customer's high level alarm did not activate; their telemetry was malfunctioning as well. Most of the acid released into the interior containment dike around the tank. No injuries occurred, customer cleaned up in house.   Customer contacted the Maine DEP as did Univar to report the event as about one cup of acid left the PVC vent of the tank onto the asphalt parking lot outside.  Packaging info in this report in questions 25, 26a, and 27 is for the customer's storage tank.

column168: On Wednesday, October 13, 2021, at approximately 8:00am a World Fuel Services, Inc. (WFS) driver was top loading a cargo tank motor vehicle. The driver was loading two separate compartments while using two different loading arms at the WFS Millersburg Bulk Plant. The first load arm’s remote-control device mechanically failed. The remote-control device’s lever got stuck in the open position and could not be closed. By the time the driver was able to force it closed, a few gallons of diesel had overflowed the compartment. The driver then panicked and went to grab spill supplies and neglected the other load arm and did not stop flow. The driver left the point of discharge without stopping flow. As the driver returned with spill clean-up supplies, the second load arm/compartment was overflowing with diesel. The driver then ran and stopped the flow on the load arm. Approximately, 300 gallons of diesel was released. The release was contained to the concrete pad that drains to an oil/water separator and dirt/gravel around to the concrete pad. All product was recovered by cleaning the concrete pad, removing impacted dirt and gravel, and by pumping out the oil/water separator. The driver reported the spill to his plant manager and was then reported to HSSE Manager. The HSSE manager then mobilized their emergency spill response contractor and notify the NRC, Ohio EPA, and LEPC. The WFS site was fully cleaned-up and all material was properly disposed of.
column169: World Fuel Services, Inc. (WFS) investigates and reviews all incidents, in order, to determine the root cause, preventability, and what actions, i.e., training or procedures, need to be conducted or implemented so that the incident will not happen again. The primary cause of the spill/release was human error, the driver did not stop flow before leaving and the secondary cause was due to the load arm’s remote-control device temporarily malfunctioning. WFS conducts multiple driver focused safety meetings during the year. On November 4, 2021, WFS briefed plant managers about the incident and its preventability and required them to review the incident with their drivers. Also, they reviewed the importance of never leaving the point of discharge and to stop all flow if you need to step away. And, reminded drivers about emergency shut offs as an option for stopping flow if the facility is equipped with one. WFS is currently making ‘Never Leave the Point of Discharge” signs to post at all load racks to serve as a visual reminder for drivers. Going forwarded all load arms will be periodically inspected for operational integrity and drivers will be instructed to report any issues discovered during loading to their manager so they can be addressed.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: On October 4, 2021, at 1400 hours, a Transportation Manager at the Frankford Yard in Philadelphia,  Pennsylvania reported that NATX 280061, a loaded tank car of UN1090, Acetone was leaking. Reportedly, there was product around the breadbox and down the side of the tank car. The tank car was immediately isolated.  The shipper, ADVANSIX, was notified via direct phone call. Marion Environmental, a Conrail emergency response  contractor, was dispatched to the Frankford Yard. Marion found that the liquid line was leaking at the threads to  the pressure plate. The valve was removed and the threads were cleaned and then rethreaded with Teflon pipe tape.  The shipper representative,  was notified of the situation found and that they would be required to obtain OTMA.   NATX 280061 is currently on hold pending finalization of the OTMA and waybill updates for transportation.

column168: FULLY LABELED HAZ-MAT SHIPMENT WAS VISUALLY DISCOVERED WET IN APPEARANCE BY THE CENTER CLERK AT THE BOXLINE-3 STATION. WITHOUT TOUCHING THE PKG HE EVACUATED THE AREA AND NOTIFIED HIS IMMEDIATE SUPERVISOR. DMP WAS CONTACTED AND WITHIN A FEW MINUTES A RESPONDER ARRIVED, DONNING THE PROPER PPE. AFTER FOLLOWING THE DECISION TREE   APPROPRIATE RESPONSE SHEET THE DAMAGE WAS CONTAINED (NO SPILLAGE OUTSIDE OF CARTON), THEN TRANSPORTED TO THE DMP PROCESSING AREA. CLOSER INSPECTION REVEALED THAT THE CAP ON 1 OF 4 PLASTIC 5-LITER JUGS WAS LOOSE BY 1/4 ROTATION, CAUSING APPROX. 10 OZ OF THE LIQUID TO LEAK THROUGH THE BREACH AND PRIMARILY INTO THE BOTTOM OF THE CARTON. THE SHIPMENT CONSISTED OF A 2-PART KIT OF SEPARATE PRODUCTS INTENDED TO BE COMBINED WHEN USED AND IT WAS THE NON HAZARDOUS PART THAT LEAKED. THE INNER PACKING MATERIAL CONSISTED OF A DOUBLE BOXED CORRUGATED CONFIGURATION AND THE OUTER CARTON WAS A SINGLEWALL FIBERBOARD BOX, RATED AT A 44 LBS/IN EDGE CRUSH TEST (ECT).

DMP RECEIVED A CALL OF A LEAKING HAZMAT AT DOOR 161 ON PD4. I (HOLLAND VANCE-WRIGHT) DONNED ALL OF OF MY PPE AND WENT TO GO RESPOND TO THE SPILL WITH A FULLY STOCKED SPILL CART. ONCE I GOT TO WHERE THE SPILL WAS LOCATED I SET UP A 15FT HOT ZONE SO NO ONE COULD GET NEAR. I MANAGED TO CLEAN UP THE ENTIRE SPILL WITH NO PROBLEMS AT ALL AND CONFIRMED TO MY SUPERVISOR THAT WE NEED TO PROCESS THE LEAKER. I THEN TOOK THE LEAKER BACK TO DMP FOR FURTHER PROCESSING.

ERTS was contacted by XPO Logistics (XFG) about a cargo release.  It was reported that due to unknown reasons, approximately 6 gallons of Rust Remover & Inhibitor (Hazardous - UN1805) was released to the trailer floor and asphalt underneath. ERTS dispatched Rock Leaf Water (RLW) to conduct cleanup operations. RLW personnel arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 10 gallons of product released. RLW personnel advised that the impacted area outside the trailer measured 8' x 20' and the impacted area of the trailer floor measured 5' x 20'.. The areas were cleaned with oil dri and neutralized with soda ash. The damaged containers were not found on the trailer. XPO personnel tracked the PRO#, and determined that the skid was taken by another driver for a delivery in Silver Lake, ND. All impacted absorbents were collected and containerized into a 55 gallon poly drum. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

SequenceEvent: Package was traveling on the IC belt to be loaded to a van, when a package handler grabbed the package off of the belt the bottom opened up as it was not properly secured with tape. One bottle fell due to the inner cardboard packing material breaking because of the weight of the bottle and the way the package handler had hold of the package. The bottle fell on its neck, broke, and rolled away which is where the spill came from. DescribePack: The neck of the bottle was broken off about an inch and a half down from the cap, completely broken off. DurationRel: 0 and MitigateEffect: Almost as soon as the bottle rolled away, it was placed upright to stop the leaking. Floor dry was spread to ensure the hazard was nulled and cleaned right away.

column168: Liquid Cargo contacted ERTS regarding the release of UN1170 Variquat B343E. It was reported that the manway on the tanker was not properly secured after a sample of the product was collected. Approximately 20-gallons of product sloshed out when the truck was driven to the loading area of the facility. ERTS dispatched an environmental contractor to respond and remediate the release. The environmental contractor utilized a Grounding & Bonding kit along with absorbent pads and hand tools to the clean the body and manway compartment of the CTMV and the adjacent 4ft x 40ft area of asphalt. All waste was collected., containerized and taken off site for pending disposal.

column168: At 1052 ET XPO Logistics Terminal notified ERTS of a 2-ounce release of UN1814 "Ferro-terj 1070" from a 330-gallon tote due to improper loading, impacting the dock. There was a small crack on the top corner of the tote. ERTS dispatched Lewis Environmental to conduct all onsite cleanup operations. At 1400 ET, Lewis personnel arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 1 gallon of product released impacted the body of the tote. The material was transferred into a new tote. The damaged tote was then cut up and containerized along with all waste into (2) 55 gallon poly drums. All waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column168: At 1854 ET, XPO Logistics Terminal notified ERTS of a cargo release at XAQ. It was reported that 55 gallons of UN 1866 “Aropol Q 6385” released from a 55 gallon metal drum that was punctured by a forklift. ERTS dispatched First Call Environmental to conduct all onsite clean up operations. At 2200 EST First Call personnel confirmed that approximately 35 gallons released  to a 7'x12', 8"x200' area of the dock and ramp also 15'x40' to the yard. Absorbents were worked into the impacted areas & collected. A pressure washer was then also utilized to clean the impacted areas after the area was neutralized with lime. The damaged drum was placed into an 85 gallon metal drum. All impacted absorbents and cleanup debris was placed into (2) 55 gallon metal drums. All waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column168: At 2143 ET, XPO Logistics Terminal notified ERTS of a cargo release at NCH. column168: AN EMPLOYEE LEFT A LARGE PLASTIC WRAPPED BUNDLE OFF AT A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL DROP POINT AS THE INNER PACKAGES WERE VISIBLE AND HAD 1.4S MARKINGS ON THEM. AN AUDITOR THEN PICKED IT UP AND BROUGHT IT BACK TO THEIR PROCESSING STATION AND ALERTED HMSC OF THE FINDING. HMSC REFERENCE NO. 175-454. AT WHICH TIME THEY WERE TOLD THE PACKAGE HAD TO BE PROCESSED IN ETT TO GET AN HM-10 SO THE AUDITOR CONTACTED THE PACKAGE SERVICE CENTER SUPERVISORS SO ONE OF THE RESPONDERS WHO HAVE ACCESS TO ETT COULD PROPERLY PROCESS IT.

PACKAGE WAS LEAKING IN AN UNLOAD TRAILER AND A RESPONDER CAME AND DONNED ALL PPE TO CLEAN UP THE SPILL. UPON BRINING IT BACK TO THE PACKAGE SERVICE CENTER A SAFETY DATA SHEET WAS LOCATED WHICH INDICATED THAT THE PACKAGE SHOULD HAVE HAD LIMITED QUANTITY MARKINGS, WHICH IT DID NOT. NIGHT SORT RMP CALLED HMSC, AND RECEIVED REFERENCE #, AND WAS TOLD TO HOLD FOR ADG COMPLIANCE.

column168: IAPX 1124 was reported to be releasing product from one of the valve boxes on the side of the car.  Inspection of the car found the liquid valve open and the liquid line closure less than tool tight.  The valve was allowed to open because the securement turnbuckle had been applied to the wrong side of the valve handle, opening the valve rather than securing it closed.  The valve was closed, the turnbuckle was applied to the correct side of the handle and the cap was resecured.
column169: Ensure all post-loading inspections are performed correctly to verify all valves are properly secured.

Landstar notified ERTS of a cargo release of UN3264 Ferric Chloride.  It was reported that approximately 2 gallons  were released from a 330-gallon tote due to the nozzle plug on the tote coming loose. The release impacted the inside of trailer and holding floor.  Hepaco personnel arrived onsite and the tote was leaking due to a valve issue.   They applied oil-dri absorbents onto the impacted areas of the trailer and dock floors. All impacted absorbents were collected and placed into a 55 gallon steel drum. Hepaco personnel departed the site with the drum of waste.

column168: Landstar notified ERTS of a a 30 gallon release of UN1170 Ethyl Alcohol from a 270-gallon tote, impacting the concrete and asphalt of a pilot gas station in Mahwah, NJ. First Call arrived on site and reported the tote was punctured by a metal track on the wall of the trailer which caused the release.  First Call transferred liquid to a new tote and transferred all original labeling when it was complete.  After First Call finished the transfer the new tote was loaded back onto the trailer.  Absorbents were used to clean the release and swept into a 55 gallon metal drum as waste.  First Call departed the site with (3) 55 gallon metal drums and damaged tote.

column62: Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails)
column168: Landstar notified ERTS of a 1-gallon (and quickly ongoing) release of UN3082" Baraklean" from a 275-gallon tote, impacting the concrete.  Allied arrived on site and located the release. There were 18 totes of Baraklean on the flat bed trailer. The trailer was on gravel parking lot behind a gas station.  Approximately 60 gallons spilled onto the gravel in a 20' x 15' area. The release is from 1 tote that was punctured by road debris that must have kicked up in transit. The hole on the tote is approximately 3/4 of the way up. Allied transferred the remaining product into a new 275 gallon tote.  They also recovered the released product that is pooled up on the gravel with a drum vac into a 55 gallon poly drum. Allied completed the tote transfer into a new 275 gallon tote. They labeled the new tote with the original label. They also scraped the impacted gravel into the same 55 gallon poly drum. Allied strapped the original tote back on the trailer and departed the site with the waste drum.

column62: Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails)
column168: At 12:36 EST XPO Logistics Terminal LHO notified ERTS of a cargo release at customer location 501 Delaney Rd, La Marque, TX. It was reported that approximately 25 gallons of UN1760 were released from a 55-gallon plastic drum due to damage caused by a pallet nail puncture The release impacted the inside of trailer and the asphalt parking lot. ERTS dispatched Lone Star Hazmat Response, LLC  to the site to complete cleanup activities.  Lonestar personnel arrived onsite at 1445 EST and confirmed 50 gallons released to 28' x 8' / 15' x 10' / 1' x 49' area of the trailer floor and concrete lot below. The team put sodium bicarb and oil dri on to the impacted areas. The damaged drum was overpacked into a 95 gallon poly drum. All clean up debris and impacted absorbents where collected and containerized into (2) 55 gallon poly drums and (1) super sack.  The waste was transported to the XPO terminal located in Houston TX for terminal personnel to manage.

column168: 1638 ET, XPO Logistics (XLA) contacted ERTS to report a regulated cargo release at a customer location. It was reported (2) 55 gallon poly drums containing UN1760 were discovered leaking due to improper loading, releasing a total of 55 gallons of the product to the trailer floor & gravel below. ERTS dispatched a contractor for clean-up. At 2021 ET, EnviroServe personnel arrived onsite. They advised (2) 55 gallon poly drums of "Spectrum" fell over inside the trailer, releasing about 85 gallons of product to the outside on gravel/soil (10' X 4') and about 5 gallons impacted a 2' X 10' area inside the trailer. Enviroserve completed clean up inside the trailer with granular absorbent, the empty drum was placed into a 95 gallon poly overpack. The other drum had about 3 gallons of product left inside, and the lid was placed back on it. Enviroserve then hand dug the impacted area outside on the gravel lot. They believe the trailer floor soaked up the majority of the release. The gravel/soil outside was believed to be only impacted by 5 gallons of product. Crew generated (2) 55 gallon poly drums containing impacted gravel and dirt. Crew utilized a power broom & had shovels, only having to dig about 2" deep.  All waste was then transported back to the XPO terminal located in La Salle, IL for terminal personnel to manage.

column168: On 10/25/2021, at 1344 hours, personnel in the CSXT Willard Yard UTLX 200592, a loaded tank car of Hydrogen Peroxide Aqueous Solutions, leaking from the top of the car. The car was isolated and the shipper, National Response Center, and Ohio EPA were notified. (CHEMTREC Report #2021-1025-00212). Specialized Professional Services, Inc, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found a ruptured frangible disc in the non-reclosing pressure relief device. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper. The shipper notified CSX Hazardous Materials Team that this tank car had experienced a similar incident involving a ruptured pressure relief device disk approximately one week prior to the reported incident. CSX Hazardous Materials Team personnel contacted the railroad and repsonse contractor of the previous incident for details, and obtained the response report. At the request of the shipper, response personnel opened and visually inspected the material in UTLX 200592, observed discoloring and solids present however no active reaction. An in-kind compatible frangible disc was provided by the shipper of record and installed. The car was held and observed for 96 hours and the continuous vent device was inspected and found to be working normally and no pressure present. The leak was secured and the car was released for transport. This incident did not require a special switching move. 7.1 is not required.  Cause Code: 441 NARRI: 40

column168: The Driver was loaded with UN 3077 (Copper Oxide) at Momentive Performance Material. The material is WWTP filter cake and this particular shipment was extremely wet.  1km after leaving the facility, the Driver applied his brakes and the liquid content sloshed up and over the trailer wall.   The bulk dump trailer is not designed to contain liquid. The top is covered with a tarp and is designed for solids and some sludges.   This particular load had a high volume of water that was sloshing around in the trailer.
column169: The Driver has been instructed not to accept loads with high water content   The preventative measure is to coordinate the packaging with the Customer (Tank for liquids, bulk for sludge)     A testable standard for water content would be ideal. Our Driver has no way of determining if the loaded material contains excess liquid. We rely on the Generator to determine what is acceptable.

column168: DURING THE PM SORT OPERATIONS AT THE FEDEX EXPRESS HUB IN MEMPHIS, TN A FIBERBOARD BOX WAS OBSERVED LEAKING. FURTHER INVESTIGATION INDICATED THE PACKAGE CONTAINED TEN 400ML CANS OF UN1950 AEROSOLS, FLAMMABLE WHICH 6 OF THE 10 CANS LEAKED FROM THE CAP ON THE CANS ONTO THE OUTER PACKAGING. FOLLOWING SPILL CLEANUP, THE INVOLVED PACKAGE WAS PLACED INSIDE A SALVAGE DRUM AND HELD PENDING FURTHER DISPOSITION INSTRUCTIONS.

PACKAGE WAS DISCOVERED AT OUR SORT FACILITY IN GREENSBORO NC. PACKAGE WAS FOUND ON BELT DURING SORT OPERATIONS. WHILE THERE WERE NO MARKINGS OR LABELS THE PACKAGE MAY CONTAINED DANGEROUS GOODS, THE BOX WAS SEEN DETERIORATING AND CHANGING COLOR WHERE THERE WAS MOISTURE. A STRONG ODOR WAS REPORTED FROM THE PACKAGE AND BEFORE BEING PLACED IN A STEEL DRUM VAPORS WERE SEEN TO BE EMITTING FROM PACKAGE WHERE FIBERBOARD BOX WAS DAMAGED. THERE WAS NO HEAT EMITTING FROM THE PACKAGE. INTERIOR OF PACKAGE WAS SEEN TO CONTAIN A PLASTIC BUCKET INSIDE OF FIBERBOARD BOX, WITH A DATA LOGGER FOR TEMPERATURE ON THE TOP OF BUCKET. PLASTIC BUBBLE WRAP WAS PLACED ON TOP OF BUCKET FOR DUNNAGE. DUE TO CONCERN OF VAPORS EMITTING FROM PACKAGE, INNER CONTENTS WERE NOT CHECKED, HOWEVER, A SALES/SHIPMENT FROM TRAVELING INSIDE THE BOX INDICATING THE FOLLOWING ITEMS: 500G OF POTASSIUM PHOSPHATE, MB; 500G POTASSIUM PHOSPHATE, DIBASIC; 500G SODIUM CHLORIDE; 500G HYDROCHLORIC ACID; 500G SODIUM HYDROXIDE. PACKAGE WAS PLACED IN A STEEL SALVAGE DRUM AND IS WAITING DISPOSITION FROM THE FAA.

column168: During the PM sort operations at the FedEx Express sort facility in Rancho Cordova, CA a fiberboard box was observed leaking. Further investigation indicated the box contained several items which included a stuffed animal, a glass bowl, socks, plastic silverware, and a bottle of Purell Advanced Hand Sanitizer which leaked inside of the outer packaging. Per the associated SDS the hand sanitizer is regulated as dangerous goods UN1987 Alcohols, N.O.S PG III. There were no dangerous goods markings or labels on the packaging, and no Shippers Declaration for Dangerous Goods was offered with the shipment. However the inner container for this product was shipped in an amount and concentration that falls under the provisions of 49CFR 173.150. Following spill cleanup, the involved package was placed inside of a salvage drum and help pending further disposition instructions.

While offloading the tote, the forklift punctured the tote, causing the sodium hypochlorite to spill into the trailer, onto the asphalt parking lot, and into the stormdrains, which were all contained on the facility's site. Central Freight Lines personnel responded and rolled the tote so that the puncture was facing up to stop the leak. They deployed granular absorbents to contain the spill and placed empty containers beneath the trailer to capture the material leaking from the trailer. HEPACO, LLC responded for cleanup. HEPACO personnel transferred the remaining product into a tote to be returned to the shipper. They cleaned the trailer floor and parking lot with granular absorbents. They flushed the parking lot and stormdrains with water until they obtained a neutral pH reading. All wash water was recovered with a vacuum and placed into drums for disposal. Waste disposal is pending and is tentatively scheduled for December 13, 2021.

column42: BATTERIES, WET, FILLED WITH ACID, ELECTRIC STORAGE
column168: PART V1:  DRIVER WAS WEST ON MISSOURI ROUTE 129 SOUTH OF SALISBURY, MO IN THE AREA OF 30840 MO-129 (GPS COORD. 39.3869401,-92.7593892). IT WAS FOGGY, RAINING AND EVERY WINDY. ROADWAY WAS COVERED WITH WATER. ROADWAY POSTED SPEED IS 60 MPH, DRIVER WAS TRAVELING APPROXIMATELY 55 MPH. THE DRIVER DROVE THROUGH SOME STANDING WATER ON THE ROADWAY AND HIT A POTHOLE IN THE ROADWAY, WHERE THE STANDING WATER WAS, THAT THE DRIVER COULD NOT SEE. THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY APPLIED HIS BRAKES AND BEGAN TO FISHTAIL, DUE TO THE WET ROAD CONDITIONS. AS THE DRIVER FISHTAILED HIS TRUCK ROLLED ONTO ITS DRIVER SIDE AND SLID TO FINAL REST. WHEN THE TRUCK ROLLED ONTO ITS SIDE, THE PRODUCT AND ELECTRIC PALLET JACK SPILLED OUT FROM THE ROOF AREA, ONTO THE SHOULDER OF THE ROADWAY. VEHICLE WAS LOADED WITH SCRAP AND NEW BATTERIES, UN2974 BATTERIES, WET FILLED WITH ACID, THEY WERE PROPERLY LOADED AND SECURED, FROM FORWARD, AFT AND SIDE TO SIDE MOVEMENT, PER DOT REGULATIONS. THE ELECTRIC PALLET JACK WEIGHS APPROXIMATELY 1,800 POUNDS, IT WAS SECURED FROM FORWARD, AFT AND SIDE TO SIDE MOVEMENT, PER DOT REGULATIONS. WHEN THE TRUCK ROLLED ONTO ITS SIDE, THE LOAD AND ELECTRIC PALLET JACK WENT VERTICALLY AND BECAME UNSECURE. EAST PENN CONTRACTED AND ENVIRONMENTAL CONTRACTOR TO DO THE CLEAN-UP. THERE WAS A TOTAL OF 282 BATTERIES AND A PALLET JACK FOR CLEAN UP. THE CONTRACTOR ADVISED THE SAFEST AND MOST EFFICIENT MEANS OF COLLECTION OF THE BATTERIES WAS TO WIPE DOWN EACH AND PALLETIZE THEM. DAMAGED BATTERIES WERE OVERPACKED. A BOX TRUCK WAS BROUGHT IN TO STAGE THE PALLETIZED AND OVERPACKED BATTERIES FOR TRANSPORT BACK TO EAST PENN MANUFACTURING CO., LYONS STATION PA FOR PROPER DISPOSAL/RECYCLE OF THE BATTERIES. THE MISSOURI DEPARTMENT OF NATURAL RESOURCES WAS ON SITE DURING THE CLEAN-UP PROCESS. THEY WERE CONTACTED BY THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT. THE COUNTY SHERIFF DEPARTMENT WAS ALSO THERE DOING TRAFFIC CONTOL FOR ABOUT 2 HOURS DURING THE CLEAN-UP. THE MISSOURI DEPARTMENT OF NATURAL RESOURCES DID OBSERVE THAT THERE WERE SOME DAMAGED BATTERIES WITH THE LEAD PLATES EXPOSED TO THE SOIL. ONCE THE CLEAN UP WAS COMPLETE THE CONTRACTOR WAS TO TAKE SOIL SAMPLES TO ASSURE THAT THERE WAS NO IMPACT TO THE SOIL. THIS WAS DONE A FEW DAYS LATER AFTER THE RAINS STOPPED. RESULTS OF THE TESTING HAVE YET BEEN RECEIVED. A REPORT WILL GO TO THE MO DCNR ONCE RECEIVED. DEPENDING ON THE RESULTS WILL DETERMINE IF REMEIDATION WILL BE NEEDED.

column42: BUTADIENES, STABILIZED OR BUTADIENES AND HYDROCARBON MIXTURE, STABILIZED CONTAINING MORE THAN 40% BUTADIENES
column168: ON MONDAY, 10/11/2021, PNR MOW FOREMAN WAS ABOUT TO BEGIN HIS MONTHLY TRACK INSPECTIONS THE INSIDE THE BORGER YARD WHEN HE NOTICED CAR CHVX 197034HAD A "SLAB OF ICE" ON ITS SIDE. MOW FOREMAN CONTACTED THE PNR OPERATIONS SUPERVISOR TO NOTIFY HER OF HIS FINDINGS.  THE PNR OPERATIONS SUPERVISOR CONTACTED CP CHEM (CAR MARK OWNER) TO NOTIFY THEM OF THE FINDINGS. CP CHEM DISPATCHED TO THE CARS LOCATION TO INSPECT. UPON THEIR INSPECTION, CP CHEM CONTACTED THE BORGER FD AND CP CHEM HAZMAT TEAM IN AN EFFORT TO RECTIFY THE SITUATION.  UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION, IT WAS DETERMINED THE CARS "A-END LIQUID VALVE SEAL" WAS "BUNCHED" ALLOWING PRODUCTS TO RELEASE FROM THE CAR. THE CP CHEM HAZMAT TEAM CORRECTED THE "SEAL" TESTED THE CAR AND DETERMINED IT WAS PROPERLY SECURED.  AFTER SECURING THE CAR, THE CP CHEM HAZMAT TEAM ALLOWED THE CAR TO SET FOR AN ADDITIONAL 30-MINUTES THEN RE-TESTED THE SEAL AND DETERMINED IT HAD PROPERLY BEEN FIXED.  AT 1309, THE SITE WAS DEEMED SAFE AND OPERATIONS COULD RESUME.
column169: 1.) PNR WILL CONDUCT A SAFETY STAND DOWN TO DISCUSS THE NAR. 2.) PNR WILL REVIEW THE PNR HAZMAT SECURITY PLAN. 3.) PNR WILL REVIW REQUIRED DOCUMENTS NEEDED TO BE AVAILABLE FOR ALL EMPLOYEES. 4.) PNR GM WILL CREATE A "ONE-PAGE"EMERGENCY RESPONSE PLAN/PROTOCOL FOR HIS TEAM IN AN EFFORT TO REDUCE RESPONSE TIME WHEN/IF ANTHER HAZMAT RELEASE OCCURS.

column168: Memphis spill office was presented a MPS of four packages containing paint UN1263 as leaking packages. While investigating the leak the spill agent discovered that three out of the four packages had a leak. Each package contained four 3.79L metal cans of paint. Two of the paint cans were a total lose and three more had lost over 75% of its contents. The inner packaging had fiberboard dividers and retainer rings. shipper was contacted and they requested that the shipment be disposed of at location.

Package was offered to the spill office located at our Memphis Hub location when it was seen plastic jerrican can containing UN 3264 was leaking. During the course of normal sort operations, a small hole developed in the bottom of the jerrican. It was not know how the hole developed. package was placed in a steel salvage drum and shipper was contacted for an amended shippers declaration for continued travel.

column168: The SPMT Star butane transloading facility is operated by Hilco Transport Inc.  At approximately 1730 on 10/18/2021 the Hilco Transport operator was disconnecting transfer hoses from tankcar. Operator did not fully close the B end liquid valve before removing hose. Approximately 1088 gallons was released in a vapor state.  Hilco transport operator paniced and went to the office for help, leaving the valve open.  Hilco operator returned to tankcar with another with another Hilco employee and was able to close the valve.
column169: Hilco Transport management conducted a safety standown on 10/20/2021 at SPMT Star NC facility.   They are retraining their operators.

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Non-Reclosing
column168: Mississippi Export Conductor was in the yard switching Rail cars and heard the PRD releasing pressure. MSE carman checked the pressure it was at 186 lbs. Once the pressure dropped to 175 lbs the PRD sealed back off. The cause was that Chevron didn't remove the nitrogen pad before loading the car causing the pressure to be to high on the car. No equipment failed and it was due to human error.
This shipment leaked from the cap. Exact cause of spill unknown. Standard spill cleanup procedures were followed.
